You are an independent skeptic verifying another agent's investigation of the RBK "Lode" subsystem (fetched-side artifact capture into GAR), in the repo at the current working directory. Do NOT trust their summary — RE-READ the cited files yourself.

Their area: provdocs (provenance attachment + public docs)

Their findings (JSON):
[
  {
    "claim": "Lode provenance rides as a reserved plain GAR tag :rbi_vouch — a FROM-scratch manifest carrying vouch.json — pushed into the SAME package as the captured base manifest. It uses no OCI referrers / subject-linking at all; it is just another tag on the package, pointed-to by the touchmark.",
    "evidence": "rbgjl02-assemble-push-vouch.sh:43-44 (`echo FROM scratch` + `COPY vouch.json /`) pushed to `${...}/${STAMP}:${_RBGL_TAG_VOUCH}` (line 37); RBSLE-lode_ensconce.adoc:123 'build a FROM scratch image copying vouch.json and push it to the Lode package under the :rbi_vouch tag — a distinct manifest sharing the one package'",
    "confidence": "high"
  },
  {
    "claim": "The vouch envelope is authored entirely in step 01 (rbgjl01) as a hand-built JSON string (no jq), staged to /workspace, and lands in two identical-content homes: the in-GAR :rbi_vouch tag and the host-side capture-file (rbf_fact_lode). It is schema-versioned (rbld-vouch-1) and explicitly unsigned today (signature: null).",
    "evidence": "rbgjl01-ensconce-capture.sh:121-139 (ENVELOPE assembly, `signature:null` at line 129, staged at line 139); RBS0-SpecTop.adoc:2180-2181 'Fields (schema rbld-vouch-1, near-term unsigned — signature: null — but schema-versioned)'; RBS0:2178 'two identical-content homes'",
    "confidence": "high"
  },
  {
    "claim": "The OCI referrers API is named in exactly ONE place in the entire spec/code corpus, as a reserved FUTURE option co-equal with cosign, gated on external trigger. It is explicitly conditional: 'once GAR maturity is confirmed.' No design work, no pace, no contract depends on it.",
    "evidence": "RBS0-SpecTop.adoc:2190 'Future signing is reserved via cosign or the OCI referrers API once GAR maturity is confirmed.' — sole hit across grep of Tools/rbk/vov_veiled and Tools/rbk",
    "confidence": "high"
  },
  {
    "claim": "No OCI referrers / subject-field implementation exists anywhere in the codebase. The only `subject` hits are SLSA DSSE-envelope subject digests (unrelated to OCI 1.1 referrers); all manifest media-type lists are standard v2/oci-index/oci-manifest. The :rbi_vouch tag-in-same-package design deliberately sidesteps referrers.",
    "evidence": "grep for referrer|oci-1.1|artifactType|subject across Tools/rbk returns zero referrers code; `subject` hits are rbgjv02-verify-provenance.py:269 (SLSA payload subject) and RBSAV-ark_vouch.adoc:114,119 (DSSE subject digest)",
    "confidence": "high"
  },
  {
    "claim": "The referrers/cosign deferral is anchored to a concrete external trigger already documented in RBSCB Deferred Items and RBSHR roadmap: external distribution / builder-strategy expansion beyond GCB. Until then SLSA v1.0 Build-Level-3 + the tag-borne vouch cover the trust claim, so signing is redundant for the current threat model (build+consume within own GCP project).",
    "evidence": "RBSCB-CloudBuildPosture.adoc:262-267 (Cosign deferral: 'redundant for the current threat model... Becomes valuable if: images are distributed externally... or builder strategy expands beyond GCB'); RBSHR-HorizonRoadmap.adoc:294 '_Trigger_: vessel ecosystem maturity and external distribution'",
    "confidence": "high"
  },
  {
    "claim": "GAR referrers support is itself a Pale (foreign-vendor, verdict-less) question — the spec language 'once GAR maturity is confirmed' frames it as waiting on Google's neighbor behavior, not on RB engineering. Verifying it is research, and the research has no consumer until the external-distribution trigger fires.",
    "evidence": "RBS0-SpecTop.adoc:2190 ('once GAR maturity is confirmed'); CMK ROE Pale doctrine (claude-cmk-roe.md 'Can I edit the source of the failure? No -> Pale') — GAR referrers maturity is uneditable vendor behavior",
    "confidence": "medium"
  },
  {
    "claim": "The public README glossary is CONCEPT-and-made-side only: it defines Enshrine, Reliquary, Bind, Graft (the old narrow capture vocabulary) but contains ZERO mentions of Lode, touchmark, or any new per-kind verb (ensconce/fetter/conclave/underpin/immure). The whole Lode subsystem is absent from the public README.",
    "evidence": "grep over README.md for lode|touchmark|ensconce|fetter|conclave|underpin|immure|augur|divine|banish returns no Lode-subsystem hits (only generic 'captures' prose at 340/431); Bind glossary at README.md:339-340, Reliquary at 325-327, Enshrine referenced at 162/327",
    "confidence": "high"
  },
  {
    "claim": "README explicitly delegates the glossary/command-reference role to CLAUDE.md, so the public README is a curated concept surface, not an exhaustive verb catalog. Per-kind verbs live in CLAUDE.md acronym maps + the veiled RBSL* specs, not README.",
    "evidence": "README.md:576 '| `├── CLAUDE.md` | Claude Code command reference, glossary, conventions |'; per-kind verbs documented in claude-rbk-tabtarget-context.md Lode section (rbw-lE/ld/lB) and RBSLE/RBSLA specs",
    "confidence": "high"
